1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 SUBCOMMITTEE RECOMMENDATION
FOR
4 HOUSE BILL NO. 1979 By: Ranson
5
6
7 SUBCOMMITTEE RECOMMENDATION
8 An Act relating to children; creating the Early
Childhood Task Force; providing for task force
9 membership; providing for election of chair and vice-
chair; permitting the selection of honorary chair;
10 directing task force to provide reports; disallowing
certain members from receiving compensation or
11 reimbursement; permitting certain members to claim
certain expenses; requiring task force to be subject
12 to the Oklahoma Open Records Act and Oklahoma Open
Meeting Act; providing that task force documents and
13 recommendations shall only be considered advice;
providing a vision statement; providing a mission;
14 providing principles the task force is to be guided
by; providing tasks for the task force; providing for
15 codification; and providing an effective date.
16
17
18 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
19 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
20 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 390 of Title 10, unless there is
21 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
22 A. There is hereby created the Early Childhood Task Force to
23 study and make recommendations to improve service access to and
24
Req. No. 16474 Page 1

1 deli very to families and children and increase the quantity of high-
2 quality early childhood services.
3 B. The task force shall be comprised of seventeen (17) members
4 to be appointed as follows:
5 1. The Director of the Department of Human Services, or a
6 designee;
7 2. The State Commissioner of Health, or a designee;
8 3. The Director of the Department of Commerce, or a designee;
9 4. The State Superintendent of Public Instruction, or a
10 designee;
11 5. The Director of the Oklahoma Health Care Authority, or a
12 designee;
13 6. A representative of the Oklahoma State Chamber appointed by
14 the Governor;
15 7. A child care provider who is a member of either the Licensed
16 Child Care Association of Oklahoma or the Oklahoma Child Care
17 Association appointed by the Department of Human Services;
18 8. A representative of an Oklahoma parent-child support
19 organization selected by the Director of the Early Childhood
20 Education Institute;
21 9. The Executive Director of Oklahoma Partnership for School
22 Readiness, or a designee;
23
24
Req. No. 16474 Page 2

1 10. A representative of the Oklahoma Association for the
2 Education of the Young Child appointed by the State Superintendent
3 of Public Instruction;
4 11. An Oklahoma State Senator selected by the President Pro
5 Tempore of the Senate;
6 12. An Oklahoma State Representative selected by the Speaker of
7 the House of Representatives;
8 13 A director of a public school early childhood program
9 appointed by the State Superintendent of Public Instruction;
10 14. A representative responsible for programs under Part C of
11 the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA) selected by
12 the State Commissioner of Health;
13 15. A representative from Oklahoma State University's
14 Department of Human Development and Family Science selected by the
15 Dean of the College of Education and Human Sciences of Oklahoma
16 State University;
17 16. A pediatric specialist selected by the Chair of the
18 Department of Pediatrics of the University of Oklahoma College of
19 Medicine; and
20 17. A representative of the Oklahoma Association of Infant
21 Mental Health appointed by the Director of the Department of Mental
22 Health and Substance Abuse Services or the Department of Psychology
23 of Oklahoma State University.
24
Req. No. 16474 Page 3

1 C. The Early Childhood Task Force shall elect a chair and vice-
2 chair, or co-chairs, from the Task Force's membership, and the chair
3 or co-chairs shall establish rules for the Task Force's meetings and
4 the conducting of business. Upon the absence or vacancy of the
5 chair, the vice-chair shall serve as chair in an acting capacity.
6 D. An honorary chair may be selected to serve in a ceremonial
7 capacity. The honorary chair shall not serve as a voting member of
8 the Task Force but may engage with the work of the Task Force in an
9 advisory role or in a manner deemed appropriate by the chair or co-
10 chairs.
11 E. The Task Force shall develop and submit an initial report to
12 the President Pro Tempore of the Senate and the Speaker of the House
13 of Representatives by November 2027 and a final report by November
14 2028.
15 F. Members shall receive no compensation or reimbursement for
16 expenses and shall serve voluntarily. Officers or employees of
17 state agencies who are appointed to the Task Force as part of their
18 duties shall be authorized to participate on the Task Force and may
19 claim subsistence, allowance, mileage, or associated expenses from
20 their respective agency budgets as permitted by law.
21 G. The Task Force shall be subject to the Oklahoma Open Records
22 Act and the Oklahoma Open Meeting Act.
23 H. Plans, reports, or recommendations of any nature adopted by
24 the Task Force shall be considered advice to the Legislature and
Req. No. 16474 Page 4

1 shal l not be construed as official policies, positions, or
2 interpretations of laws, rules, or regulations by any department or
3 agency of state government, nor shall any such department or agency
4 be bound in any manner to consider such advice when conducting its
5 advisory and regulatory affairs.
6 I. The Task Force shall be guided by the following vision
7 statement: Oklahoma children, especially those between zero (0) and
8 five (5) years of age, deserve healthy childhoods that are supported
9 by a robust early childhood system which improves outcomes and
10 effectively provides high-quality early care and education, improves
11 and enhances school readiness, adapts to the needs of families and
12 communities, and is equitably accessible to all communities across
13 the state.
14 J. The Task Force shall work towards the mission of creating a
15 framework for a more efficient and effective governance structure
16 for early childhood programming, such as a coordinated,
17 consolidated, or new independent agency.
18 K. The Task Force's work shall be guided by a commitment to the
19 following principles:
20 1. Children, family, and community well-being shall be centered
21 throughout the Early Childhood Task Force's work;
22 2. Efforts shall be focused on maximizing efficiencies to
23 reduce the administrative burdens on families and improve access to
24
Req. No. 16474 Page 5

1 earl y childhood services through the creation of a new governance
2 structure;
3 3. Any possible consolidation of early childhood services shall
4 be informed by what families and communities say are wanted and
5 needed;
6 4. Access to programs and services shall be equitable and
7 available to all children and families regardless of socioeconomic
8 status or geographic location;
9 5. Intentional focus shall be placed on developing strategies
10 to reach families and young children in health care, early
11 education, and care deserts or furthest from opportunity and
12 existing resources;
13 6. Access to affordable and quality health care, nutrition,
14 early education and care, mental health, home visiting, early
15 intervention, support for families, early learning, and other
16 services in the critical prenatal to five-year-age period will
17 decisively impact academic success, economic development
18 opportunities, and the prosperity of Oklahoma;
19 7. Efforts shall be made to use data-informed approaches and
20 explore better ways to develop shared data systems;
21 8. Work shall focus on strengthening and expanding the early
22 education and care delivery system already in use in Oklahoma;
23
24
Req. No. 16474 Page 6

1 9. Alignment across sectors and state agencies shall increase
2 capacity, maximize funding, and create a more streamlined delivery
3 of services;
4 10. The importance of growing a well-educated and well-
5 supported early childhood workforce shall remain at the forefront
6 and be informed by the Task Force's work;
7 11. While focusing on advancing the delivery system, work shall
8 highlight the importance of defining quality care and expanding
9 capacity and access to create a greater quantity of quality
10 services;
11 12. To incentivize innovation and respond to family needs,
12 communities must be empowered to develop local, community-based
13 solutions that take a whole-child and whole-family approach in
14 responding to needs;
15 13. To ensure holistic childhood well-being and improve health
16 outcomes, there must be alignment between state efforts to improve
17 early learning and care and existing prenatal and maternal health
18 initiatives; and
19 14. Strengthening early childhood developmental health is vital
20 to ensuring that children are prepared to achieve academic success
21 and are prepared for lifelong learning.
22 L. The Task Force's duties shall include:
23 1. Conducting an analysis of the current early childhood
24 delivery system in Oklahoma and how it is financed with specific
Req. No. 16474 Page 7

1 focu s on gaps, inefficiencies, and redundancies. This work should
2 focus on how creating a new governance structure for early childhood
3 services could overcome these challenges and improve how care is
4 delivered, accessed, and funded. This analysis must specifically
5 include:
6 a. a review of current early childhood programs and
7 policies dispersed between the Department of Human
8 Services, State Department of Health, Department of
9 Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services, State
10 Department of Commerce, Oklahoma Health Care
11 Authority, and the State Department of Education. The
12 review should pay special attention to where current
13 statutory authority over certain operations exists and
14 where possible areas of redundancy occur,
15 b. a review of how current funding systems blend and
16 various funding opportunities, with special attention
17 as to how funding streams are currently utilized for
18 early childhood programs that are housed across
19 departments. This fiscal review should map the routes
20 all private, public, federal, and state funding
21 streams take from funding authority to program
22 application,
23 c. a review of how Oklahoma might integrate existing
24 programming into a consolidated delivery system and
Req. No. 16474 Page 8

1 what needs might exist for new programming that the
2 state currently lacks,
3 d. recommendations on how cross-agency collaboration and
4 partnerships can be fostered to develop a whole-of-
5 government approach to strengthening the delivery of
6 early childhood services, specifically ensuring that
7 data infrastructure is integrated across agencies,
8 account for both qualitative and quantitative methods,
9 and can be widely utilized by multiple state agencies,
10 e. recommendations on how a new governance structure
11 might maximize efficiencies for early childhood
12 providers and their workforce. This work should
13 determine how licensing, workforce development and
14 support, and facility review can be improved to
15 eliminate barriers to entry for providers and
16 professionals. This should also include a review of
17 current regulatory structures that complicate the
18 process of entering the early childhood sector,
19 f. recommendations on how a new governance structure can
20 strengthen the existing health care workforce to
21 better support the development of young children and
22 well-being of mothers through improved access to
23 comprehensive and preventive care. This should also
24 include a review of how to secure improved health
Req. No. 16474 Page 9

1 outcomes for children, financial sustainability of
2 delivery models, and cultivating workforce pipelines,
3 and
4 g. an analysis of key lessons learned from states already
5 advancing consolidated systems of early childhood
6 governance to inform Oklahoma's own process;
7 2. Conducting a series of stakeholder engagement opportunities
8 to elicit feedback on the current early childhood governance
9 structure and better understand the needs of parents, families,
10 providers, and businesses;
11 3. Following the engagement of stakeholders, the Task Force
12 shall conduct a review that synthesizes feedback received from
13 families, providers, community leaders, and the business sector.
14 This review shall include recommendations on how the state delivery
15 system and governance model can be improved to respond to family and
16 community needs. It shall also include recommendations for how the
17 state can better engage with parents, families, and communities on a
18 regular basis to ensure family voice is centered in the work of
19 state agencies;
20 4. Drafting a proposed transition plan to ensure the continuous
21 operation of state services upon the creation of a new governance
22 structure for early childhood. This plan shall:
23 a. include detailed recommendations for what programs and
24 services should remain in their current place or
Req. No. 16474 Page 10

1 transition into a new governance structure. Each
2 recommendation shall consider the challenges and
3 benefits of moving programs,
4 b. focus on movement between agencies and how
5 collaboration can be strengthened with nonexecutive
6 agencies. It shall also include recommendations for
7 any necessary interagency agreements,
8 c. include a review of what additional funding, if any,
9 and resources, if any, might be needed to transition
10 to a new governance structure effectively and
11 efficiently, and
12 d. provide recommended goals and metrics for the new
13 entity to strive towards once operational; and
14 5. Drafting proposed legislation that creates a new governance
15 structure that oversees Oklahoma's early childhood education and
16 care programs.
17 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
